President Barack Obama has proclaimed October 2015 as National Cybersecurity Awareness Month in order to raise awareness about the importance of cybersecurity and to encourage individuals to take steps to protect themselves online. The President emphasizes the need for vigilance against cyber threats and the importance of safeguarding critical infrastructure networks. The government is working to promote information sharing between the public and private sectors and has launched the Cybersecurity Framework to help identify and respond to cybersecurity incidents. The Department of Homeland Security's "Stop.Think.Connect." campaign provides tools and resources to help individuals confront cyber threats. The President urges Americans to choose stronger passwords, update software, and practice responsible online behavior to decrease their susceptibility to cyber attacks. The proclamation highlights the reliance on the Internet and the need for continued awareness and attention to cybersecurity in order to protect the digital infrastructure of the United States.